theorem closure_inter_interior_compl_eq_empty {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X]
    (A : Set X) :
    closure A ∩ interior (Aᶜ) = (∅ : Set X) := by
  ext x
  constructor
  · intro hx
    -- `x` lies both in `closure A` and in `interior (Aᶜ)`.
    have hx_cl : x ∈ closure A := hx.1
    have hx_int : x ∈ interior (Aᶜ) := hx.2
    -- Any neighbourhood of `x` meets `A`; in particular `interior (Aᶜ)`.
    have h_nonempty :
        ((interior (Aᶜ)) ∩ A : Set X).Nonempty :=
      ((mem_closure_iff).1 hx_cl) isOpen_interior hx_int
    -- But `interior (Aᶜ)` is contained in `Aᶜ`, so the intersection is empty.
    rcases h_nonempty with ⟨y, hy⟩
    have hYnAᶜ : y ∈ Aᶜ := interior_subset hy.1
    have : False := hYnAᶜ hy.2
    exact this.elim
  · intro hx
    -- `x ∈ ∅` is impossible, so from it we can derive anything.
    cases hx

theorem interior_subset_interior_closure_of_subset
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A B : Set X} (hAB : A ⊆ B) :
    interior A ⊆ interior (closure B) := by
  -- First, upgrade the inclusion `A ⊆ B` to `A ⊆ closure B`.
  have h₁ : (A : Set X) ⊆ closure B := by
    intro x hx
    have : x ∈ B := hAB hx
    exact subset_closure this
  -- Monotonicity of `interior` yields the desired result.
  exact interior_mono h₁
